Being on top of the JVM is also one of the really nice things about Rhino (Mozilla's JVM based JavaScript interpreter: <a href="http://www.mozilla.org/rhino/" rel="nofollow">http://www.mozilla.org/rhino/</a>). You have access to a zillion Java libraries. Taking two of their examples:<p>MySQL:<p><pre><code>    var conn = java.sql.DriverManager.getConnection("jdbc:mysql://"+host+"/"+db+"?user="+user+"&password="+password),
        statement = conn.createStatement(),
        resultset = statement.executeQuery("SELECT * FROM test");
        // do stuff!

</code></pre>
Jetty also works from Rhino:<p><pre><code>    var server = new Packages.org.mortbay.jetty.Server(8080);

    server.setHandler(new Packages.org.mortbay.jetty.handler.AbstractHandler({
        handle: function(target, request, response, dispatch){
            // do stuff!
            request.setHandled(true);
        }
    }));
    server.start();
</code></pre>
Obviously these could be wrapped up in more JavaScripty libraries, but all the hard work is done for you.
